{{about|a type of rock found in British Columbia|the definition of someone from Dallas, Texas|Dallas, Texas}}
'''Dallasite''' is a [[breccia]] made of subequant to rectangular or distinctly elongate, curvilinear shards that represent the spalled rims of [[Pillow lava|pillow basalt]] (see: [[Hyaloclastite]]). This material is commonly partly altered to [[Chlorite group|chlorite]], [[epidote]], [[quartz]] and [[Carbonate minerals|carbonate]], for which the local term 'dallasite' has been coined.<ref>[https://www.researchgate.net/publication/266289964_High-Mg_Lavas_in_the_Karmutsen_Flood_Basalts_Northern_Vancouver_Island_NTS_092L_Stratigraphic_Setting_and_Metallogenic_Significance]{{citation|title=High-Mg Lavas in the Karmutsen Flood Basalts, Northern Vancouver Island (NTS 092L): Stratigraphic Setting and Metallogenic Significance|date=2008|author=Nixon, G.T., Larocque, J., Pals, A., Styan, J., Greene, A.R., and Scoates, J.S.}}</ref> The stone dallasite is named after Dallas Road, [[Victoria, British Columbia]]. It is considered the unofficial stone of British Columbia's capital city.<ref>{{citation | author = Hudson Rick | title = A Field Guide to Gold, Gemstone and Mineral Sites of British Columbia. Volume 2. Orca Book Publishers. | date = 1999}}</ref> Dallasite is found in [[Triassic]] [[volcanic rock]]s of [[Vancouver Island]] and is considered the third most important [[Gemstone|gem]] material in British Columbia.<ref>{{citation | author = VanLandingham, Sam L. | title = Geology of world gem deposits | date = 1985}}</ref>
