{{Nuclear physics}}
[[File:Phases of Nuclear Matter.JPG|thumb|280px|Phases of nuclear matter with equal numbers of neutrons and protons; Compare with Siemens & Jensen.<ref name=Siemens>{{cite book |title=Elements Of Nuclei: Many-body Physics With The Strong Interaction |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z-8vuyAqT9MC&pg=PA347 |author=Phillip John Siemens |author2=Aksel S. Jensen |isbn=0-201-62731-0 |publisher=[[Westview Press]] |date=1994}}</ref>]]
'''Nuclear matter''' is an idealized system of interacting nucleons ([[proton]]s and [[neutron]]s) that exists in several [[phase (matter)|phase]]s that as yet are not fully established.<ref name=Durand>
{{cite book |title=Nuclear dynamics in the nucleonic regime |author=Dominique Durand |author2=Eric Suraud |author3=Bernard Tamain |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9obAY54qb30C&pg=PA4 |page=4 |isbn=0-7503-0537-1 |date=2001 |publisher=[[CRC Press]] }} </ref> It is ''not'' matter in a nucleus, but a hypothetical substance consisting of a huge number of protons and neutrons interacting by only [[nuclear force]]s and ''no'' [[Coulomb force]]s.<ref name=Mattuck>
{{cite book |title=A Guide to Feynman Diagrams in the Many-body Problem |author=Richard D. Mattuck |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pe-v8zfxE68C&pg=PA92 |isbn=0-486-67047-3 |date=1992 |publisher=[[Courier Dover Publications]] |edition=Reprint of 1974 McGraw-Hill second}}</ref><ref name=Walecka>
{{cite book |title=Theoretical nuclear and subnuclear physics |author=John Dirk Walecka |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mfphXc8b-2IC&pg=PA18 |page=18 |isbn=981-238-898-2 |date=2004 |publisher=[[World Scientific]] |edition=2}}
</ref> Volume and the number of particles are infinite, but the ratio is finite.<ref name=Hofmann>
{{cite book |title=The Physics of Warm Nuclei: With Analogies to Mesoscopic Systems |author=Helmut Hofmann |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JIX5bIkQks0C&pg=PA36 |page=36 |date=2008 |isbn=0-19-850401-2 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]}}</ref> Infinite volume implies no surface effects and translational invariance (only differences in position matter, not absolute positions).
A common idealization is ''symmetric nuclear matter'', which consists of equal numbers of protons and neutrons, with no electrons.
When nuclear matter is compressed to sufficiently high density, it is expected, on the basis of the [[asymptotic freedom]] of [[Quantum chromodynamics]], that it will become [[quark matter]], which is a degenerate Fermi gas of quarks.<ref name=Alford>
{{cite book |editor= Armen Sedrakian |editor2= John Walter Clark |editor3= Mark Gower Alford |chapter=Phase diagram of neutral quark matter at moderate densities |title=Pairing in fermionic systems |author=Stefan B Rüster |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HlW_DXqKvLUC&pg=PA19 |isbn=981-256-907-3 |date=2007 |publisher=World Scientific}}
</ref> [[File:Neutron star structure.JPG|thumb|275px|Cross-section of neutron star. Densities are in terms of ''ρ<sub>0</sub>'' the saturation nuclear matter density, where nucleons begin to touch. Patterned after Haensel ''et al.'',<ref name=Haensel>{{cite book |title=Neutron Stars |author=Paweł Haensel |author2=A Y Potekhin |author3=D G Yakovlev |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iIrj9nfHnesC&printsec=frontcover#PPA12,M1 |isbn=0-387-33543-9 |publisher=Springer |date=2007}}</ref> page 12]] Some authors use "nuclear matter" in a broader sense, and refer to the model described above as "infinite nuclear matter",<ref name=Siemens/> and consider it as a "toy model", a testing ground for analytical techniques.<ref name="Müther">
{{cite book |title=Nuclear methods and the nuclear equation of state |editor=Marcello Baldo |chapter=Dirac-Brueckner approach for finite nuclei |author=Herbert Müther |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e3xeCXHJq6wC&pg=PA170 |page=170 |isbn=981-02-2165-7 |publisher=World Scientific |date=1999}}
</ref> However, the composition of a [[neutron star]], which requires more than neutrons and protons, is not necessarily locally charge neutral, and does not exhibit translation invariance, often is differently referred to, for example, as ''neutron star matter'' or ''stellar matter'' and is considered distinct from nuclear matter.<ref name=Raduta>
{{cite book |title=Collective Motion and Phase Transitions in Nuclear Systems |chapter=Nuclear matter versus stellar matter |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lQVw1Sh6XcgC&pg=PA392 |date=2007 |publisher=World Scientific |author=Francesca Gulminelli |isbn=981-270-083-8 |editor=A. A. Raduta |editor2=V. Baran |editor3=A. C. Gheorghe |display-editors = 3 |editor4=I. Ursu}}
</ref><ref name=Glendenning>
{{cite book |title=Compact stars |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BBSOgxe2S1AC&pg=PA242 |page=242 |author=Norman K. Glendenning |isbn=0-387-98977-3 |date=2000 |edition=2 |publisher=Springer}}
</ref> In a neutron star, pressure rises from zero (at the surface) to an unknown large value in the center.
Methods capable of treating finite regions have been applied to stars and to atomic nuclei.<ref name=Lenske>
{{cite journal |title=Density dependent hadron field theory for asymmetric nuclear matter and exotic nuclei |author=F. Hofmann |author2=C. M. Keil |author3=H. Lenske |arxiv=nucl-th/0007050 |journal=Phys. Rev. C|date=2001 |volume =64|bibcode = 2001PhRvC..64c4314H |doi = 10.1103/PhysRevC.64.034314 |issue=3 }}
</ref><ref name=Rabhi>
{{cite journal |title=Stellar matter with a strong magnetic field within density-dependent relativistic models |doi=10.1088/0954-3899/35/12/125201 |author=A. Rabhi |author2=C. Providencia |author3=J. Da Providencia |journal =J Phys G |volume=35 |date=2008 |arxiv=0810.3390 |pages=125201 |bibcode = 2008JPhG...35l5201R |issue=12 }}</ref> One such model for finite nuclei is the [[Semi-empirical mass formula#The liquid drop model and its analysis|liquid drop model]], which includes surface effects and Coulomb interactions.
