{{refimprove|date=August 2017}}
'''Slash-and-char''' is an alternative to [[slash-and-burn]] that has a lesser effect on the [[Environment (biophysical)|environment]]. It is the practice of [[charring]] the [[biomass]] resulting from the slashing, instead of burning it. The resulting residue matter [[charcoal]] can be utilized as [[biochar]] to [[soil conditioner|improve the soil fertility]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Biederman|first=L. A.|date=2012-12-31|title=Biochar and its effects on plant productivity and nutrient cycling: a meta-analysis|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/gcbb.12037|journal=GCB Bioenergy|language=en|volume=5|issue=2|pages=202-214|doi=10.1111/gcbb.12037}}</ref>

In that context, [[charcoal]] can be made by numerous and varied methods, from [[Charcoal#History|the simplest]] (an earth cover on the pile of wood, with strategically placed vents) to the most sophisticated (a modern equipment or plant that recuperates and processes strictly all exhaust gases into [[pyroligneous acid]] and [[syngas]]).

Slash-and-char offers considerable benefits to the environment when compared to [[slash-and-burn]].{{cn|date=August 2017}}

It results in the creation of biochar, which can then be mixed with biomass such as [[crop residue]]s, [[food waste]], or [[manure]], and buried in the soil to bring about the formation of [[terra preta]]. Terra preta is one of the richest soils on the planet – and the only one known to regenerate itself. 

It moreover sequesters considerable quantities of [[CO2 sequestration|carbon]] in the safest and most beneficial fashion, as opposite to the negative effects of the slash-and-burn. Switching to slash-and-char can sequester up to 50% of the carbon in a highly stable form.<ref> Lehmann – Biochar sequestration in terrestrial ecosystems,'' supra'' note 11 at 407 (“If this woody aboveground [[biomass]] were converted into biochar by means of simple kiln techniques and applied to soil, more than 50% of this C would be sequestered in a highly stable form.”)</ref>
The nascent [[carbon emission trading|carbon trading]] market that sponsors [[CO2 sequestration|{{CO2}} sequestration]] projects, could therefore help supplement the farmers' income while supporting a decrease in the pace of [[deforestation]] and the development of a more [[sustainable agriculture]].

